That’s a vivid extension of your tracer metaphor. In real systems work, people often do something very similar: inject multiple tracers to see how different pathways compete or interact. The point isn’t just which one “wins,” but what the race reveals about the structure of the system.

Here are a few things that multi-dye tests tend to show:

⸻

1. Pathway Efficiency

Different tracers can move at different speeds depending on the routes available.

dye A → shortest / lowest-resistance path
dye B → slower path
dye C → trapped in eddies

Watching that race reveals where the high-capacity channels really are.

⸻

2. Bottlenecks and Convergence

Sometimes several dyes converge at the same choke point. That tells you the system has a shared constraint—a place where everything must pass through.

In networks, that might be a key node or protocol; in social systems, it could be a shared resource or decision point.

⸻

3. Mixing vs. Segregation

If the dyes quickly blend, the system mixes information or influence rapidly.
If they stay separate, the system may have compartments or boundaries that keep flows distinct.

⸻

4. Feedback Loops

Occasionally a tracer circles back toward where it started. That indicates a feedback loop, which often drives reinforcement or stabilization in complex systems.

⸻

5. The Human Element

Your “cheering on your side” comment touches on something important: once people start watching competing ideas or signals, they naturally develop preferences. That can affect the system itself—attention and support can change which pathways grow stronger.

So the observer isn’t completely neutral; interest and attention can become part of the flow.

⸻

In the end, the value of the race isn’t really the winner.
It’s that the competition between tracers makes the hidden architecture of the system easier to see—which routes are open, where resistance exists, and how feedback shapes the outcome.